body:
Closes #4993

1. This definitely shouldn't go in Cython 3.0 (not that I think there's a huge danger of that).
2. It requires fairly significant runtime support, so won't work at all on Python <3.11 (in principle I guess we could implement our own BaseExceptionGroup and ExceptionGroup class on these versions, but it really doesn't seem worth it).
3. I still don't really understand `except*` (but I do know how it's implemented)

comment_data.body:
We have lots of "helper" nodes that are not called "helpers" because they do more than just helping. This one basically implements an `except*` construct, so let's call it that.
```suggestion
class ExceptStarChainNode(StatListNode):
    """
    Implements an 'except*' handler (Python 3.11+ / PEP-654).
    See https://docs.python.org/3/reference/compound_stmts.html#except-star

    Uses a stat list node for implementation (since it's
    mostly implemented in terms of a generated tree of other nodes).
    However, also handles some of
    the temporary variables that its children will need.

    The advantage of this is that approach is that a lot can be handled
    by the existing flow control structures
    """
```

EDIT: although, it's not `except*`, it's more an `except*`-chain, right? So maybe `ExceptStarGroupNode` or `ExceptStarChainNode` ?

comment_data.body: I'm surprised that the `ExceptClauseNode` does not know whether it's `except` or `except*`. That seems to be the reason why you need to know up-front whether we're parsing one or the other. Wouldn't it be enough to just parse the clause and then ask it whether it's `except` or `except*`?

comment_data.body:
I've changed this to be stored on `ExceptClauseNode` and with "cannot have both except and except*" enforced afterwards. I agree this is simpler.

I think the original version was an overly-literal translation of the Python grammar (where except and except* are considered different and unrelated to each other)
